ving religious control irked the Oblates, who put up stiff resistance, betraying their reticence to the liberalization of higher education. While the government valued social policy, the Oblates focused on educating individuals.  Although the Oblates ultimately lost, history is as relevant as ever, and this book comes at a time when social planning is becoming increasingly prevalent within universities.  Published in English.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChurch and collegezOntariozOttawa. 0aChurch and college. 0aSecularizationzOntariozOttawa. 0aSecularization. 0aUniversity of Ottawa-History. 7aEDUCATION / History.2bisacsh  aCatholic History.  aChurch-State relations.  aHigher Education.  aSecularization.  aUniversity History.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311127253508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020z978311127473740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780776629117?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780776629117423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780776629117/original  a978-3-11-127253-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-127473-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles